It makes me wonder, especially in light of restaurants having to eliminate outdoor dining, to what extent supporting culturally or economically significant businesses is the responsibility of the government vs. the broader community.
What do you folks think?
Well for the government, I think they should recognize when a business is benefiting the growth and economy of the city, and if so they have some incentive to help out
On the community side, I'm kind of less certain
Because in some sense the community is the culture, so if they deem the business not as significant then there's another issue
Idk if that makes any sense

I think that the onus is sometimes put on the regular consumer to an excessive degree, a similar thing is with climate change where the narrative is that the normal consumer needs to fix their carbon footprint asap when in reality companies do most of the damage, and if a business has a bigger significance then it should get support at the administrative level as well as the community level
